anManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents with a three day history of fever, cough and malaise. Now he has developed increasingly painful lesions on his legs and a few spots around his mouth. He is not taking any medications except paracetamol for fever and has no history of any drug or other allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has a temperature of 38.7 \u00b0C and his other vital signs are within normal limits. The lesion around his mouth (Image 1) and on his legs are shown (Image 2). Chest auscultation reveals faint crackles in the right lower lung field and the rest of the systemic examination is normal. A chest X-ray shows an ill-defined opacity in the right lower lobe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Staphylococcal scalded skin syndrome","Erythema multiforme major","Toxic epidermal necrolysis","Herpetic gingivostomatitis","Kawasaki disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe prodromal period preceding the appearance of the rash, together with the chest auscultation findings and the chest X-ray suggesting an atypical pneumonia, point to a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema multiforme major (EM major)\u003C/strong\u003E caused by Mycoplasma pneumoniae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOral mucosal lesions can be bullous and erosive with haemorrhagic crusts are common (genital and ocular mucosa are less commonly involved). The leading cause of \u003Cstrong\u003EEM major\u003C/strong\u003E is herpes simplex virus infection, followed by Mycoplasma pneumoniae and other viral or bacterial infections or drugs. The rash appears target-like but is bullous centrally. Mycoplasma-induced rash and mucositis (MIRM) is a variant of EM major where mucositis is the leading presentation rather than rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcal scalded skin syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (Ritter disease) is caused by the epidermolytic exotoxin that is produced by some strains of Staphylococcus and usually follows a localised infection from the upper respiratory tract, ears, conjunctiva, or umbilical stump. The rash typically starts on the face and flexures (groin, axillae, and neck) with erythema and fissures that progress to large, thin blisters that ultimately exfoliate. Mucosal involvement is uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic epidermal necrolysis i\u003C/strong\u003Es most commonly triggered by medications in both adults and children and is characterized by extensive necrosis and detachment of the epidermis of mucocutaneous surfaces. Toxic epidermal necrolysis with paracetamol is very rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpetic gingivostomatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common manifestation of primary herpes simplex virus (HSV) infection in children. Ocular and pulmonary involvement are not common with herpes infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease, \u003C/strong\u003Ealso called mucocutaneous lymph node syndrome, presents in relatively younger children. Kawasaki disease presents with fever, conjunctivitis, extremity erythema and rash, cervical lymphadenopathy, and polymorphous eruption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema multiforme major is often caused by herpes simplex virus infection, followed by Mycoplasma pneumoniae and other viral or bacterial infections or drugs.","M.\u00a0pneumoniae\u00a0infections may produce both pulmonary and extrapulmonary diseases.","Mycoplasma-induced rash and mucositis (MIRM) is a variant of EM major where mucositis is the leading presentation rather than rash."],"references":["Hafsi W, Badri T. Erythema Multiforme. [Updated 2023 Mar 16]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470259/","Gordon O, Oster Y, Michael-Gayego A, et al. The Clinical Presentation of Pediatric Mycoplasma pneumoniae Infections-A Single Center Cohort. Pediatr Infect Dis J 2019; 38:698.","American Academy of Pediatrics. Herpes simplex. In: Red Book: 2021-2024 Report of the Committee on Infectious Diseases, 32nd ed, Kimberlin DW, Barnett ED, Lynfield R, Sawyer MH (Eds), American Academy of Pediatrics, Itasca, IL 2021. p.407.","Burns JC, Mason WH, Glode MP, et al. Clinical and epidemiologic characteristics of patients referred for evaluation of possible Kawasaki disease. United States Multicenter Kawasaki Disease Study Group. J Pediatr 1991; 118:680.","Stern RS, Divito SJ. Stevens-Johnson Syndrome and Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis: Associations, Outcomes, and Pathobiology-Thirty Years of Progress but Still Much to Be Done. J Invest Dermatol 2017; 137:1004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32110"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20722"},{"type":"media","id":"20723"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20722"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w5uyV15RhcRwL687lb2wkBrRuRvGxM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/w5uyV15RhcRwL687lb2wkBrRuRvGxM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20723"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4HZpOgDhgzMqpK5UOPlkznpSr602gl.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4HZpOgDhgzMqpK5UOPlkznpSr602gl.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":320,"height":240}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co